"Don't miss your shot" to be a part of the conversation with this award-winning biographer!

Ron Chernow, author of the best-selling biography of Alexander Hamilton and collaborator on the award-winning musical "Hamilton," will appear at an evening forum tomorrow, Nov. 15, as part of the Presidential Lecture Series.

Brian Lamb, founder and executive chairman of C-SPAN and a Purdue alumnus, will interview Chernow and moderate a question-and-answer session with the audience as part of the forum, to be held at Loeb Playhouse in Stewart Center from 6-7:15 p.m. Doors will open at 5:30 p.m. A pre-forum reception is scheduled from 5-5:45 p.m. in the west lobby outside Loeb. All events are free and open to the public, as capacity allows.

https://www.purdue.edu/convocations/event/conversation-with-hamilton-biographer-ron-chernow/
link_name: A Conversation with Ron Chernow - Purdue Convocations

This weekend is the Military Appreciation Day football game! Purdue Football will face Cincinnati Bearcats Football in West Lafayette on Saturday in a game dedicated to supporting our nation's veterans. Purdue's Boilers 4 Heroes campaign, in partnership with the Entrepreneurship Bootcamp for Veterans with Disabilities (EBV), is committed to helping veterans have a successful transition into civilian life. The Purdue football team will also display its support for our troops.

"Purdue University Olympians won four medals in Rio, including alumna Amanda Elmore who won a gold in rowing for the U.S. women's eight rowing team. Elmore is the first female Purdue Olympian to win a gold, and the fifth Boilermaker to win an Olympic gold medal since 1900. Purdue alumnus David Boudia and student Steele Johnson also won silver medals in synchronized diving, and Boudia earned a bronze in the individual 10-meter platform diving."

Blake Vogt is one of the most respected magicians in the industry, and has created magic for David Copperfield, David Blaine, Dynamo, along with many other top magicians around the world. He has also created visual elements for Avicii, Pharrell, and Kanye West as well as lent his expertise to movies such as Now You See Me 1 & 2, and Marvel's Ant Man. TV highlights include performing on Penn & Teller: Fool Us, Wizard Wars on Syfy, and Fox's 2015 New Year's Eve Special. Blake recently trained and consulted Daniel Radcliffe, Jesse Eisenberg, Mark Ruffalo, and Dave Franco for Now You See Me 2 in London. 

Learn more at http://www.blakevogt.com/ and don't forget to cheer on this Boilermaker!

Join us in celebrating the life of aviation pioneer Amelia Earhart!

Today we remember and honor the great Amelia Earhart on #AmeliaEarhartDay. During her time here at Purdue, Earhart served as a Consultant in the Department for the Study of Careers for Women and Technical Advisor in the Department of Aeronautics. She became a leading example of a successful woman for female students and was an inspiration to many. Purdue's Earhart residence hall is named after her and a statue of her stands at its entrance to greet students.

Bruce Applegate, Purdue associate professor in the Department of Food Science, and collaborators from the University of Tennessee have developed an add-on process to milk pasteurization that adds up to seven more weeks to milk's shelf life. The process involves rapid heating and cooling of milk which significantly reduces the amount of harmful bacteria present. http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2016/Q3/rapid,-low-temperature-process-adds-weeks-to-milks-shelf-life.html

Scott Tingle, Purdue's 23rd and most recent astronaut, has an interesting feat to accomplish. Tingle, who will be traveling to space come September 2017, has been chosen to take with him several Purdue items. Among the list is the half-pound Neil A. Armstrong medal and a placard that reads, "Don't Worry/I'm a Mechanical Engineer."
 
Mitch Daniels spoke about the task stating, "Seeing this latest astronaut alumnus take his Boiler Pride into space speaks to just how far a Purdue education can take you."
 
Tingle joins the ranks of Boilermaker astronauts who continue to prove that the sky is certainly not the limit for our students. Read on to learn more about the September Expedition. 

https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2016/Q2/purdue-items-picked-to-go-into-space-in-2017-mission-with-alumnus.html

Last year, Lisa and Dick Brown's beloved dogs Bailey and George were diagnosed with cancer. George lost his fight less than three months from the time of diagnosis. In his name and in Bailey's they are committed to finding a cure for cancer in dogs and remain hopeful that Dr. Knapp and her team at Purdue will be victorious. Today, the Brown's generously supported the College of Veterinary Medicine and Dr. Knapp's mission with the Purdue Comparative Oncology Program.

"Cancer is a terrible disease. It deprives all of us, both humans and dogs, of life. When a life is lost the universe mourns," says Lisa.

We appreciate your support, Lisa and Dick. From all of us...

Audio from the Apollo 10 flight in 1969 is creating quite the buzz, and Purdue alumnus Eugene Cernan who graduated from Purdue University in 1956 with a degree in Electrical Engineering, earned a Master's degree in 1963, and who was on the flight said, "I don't remember that incident exciting me enough to take it seriously. It was probably just radio interference. Had we thought it was something other than that we would have briefed everyone after the flight. We never gave it another thought."

Link to the in-flight audio clip (sounds begin at 2:50): http://history.nasa.gov/ap10fj/audio/a10o-1021010.mp3

The following is a statement from Steve Schultz, Purdue legal counsel, on the recent controversy related to an online post by a part-time Purdue staff member:

"As we've already indicated, a threat of rape is outside the bounds of any definition of protected speech. And if it appeared that Mr. Newman had any such intention, he would have been terminated immediately. But the police investigation tells us that there was, and is, no real threat to the campus community.  That finding does not foreclose the possibility of other employment-related actions based on Purdue's internal complaint processes.

"The disruption we've endured as a community is entirely due to Mr. Newman's online posts.  Anything other than a full apology and explanation from him about the intent of his statement will be insufficient to cure the harm he's done.

"It's fortunate for Mr. Newman that he works at a public university both obligated under the First Amendment and committed by principle to protect free speech -- even speech as abhorrent as his.  Had he uttered such an outrageous and vulgar statement while working for a private college or other private employer, he would almost certainly have been fired on the spot.  Mr. Newman's obnoxious rhetoric is an embarrassment for Purdue, but our special obligations as a public institution impose a much higher threshold before condemnation can be extended to punishment."

A Purdue University archaeologist and associate professor of anthropology is returning to Tombos, Sudan, to excavate tombs in the Nile River Valley and research the Egyptian and Nubian cultures from thousands of years ago. Today, we remember the three lost in the unfortunate events of the Apollo I accident in 1967, two of which were Boilermakers (left to right):
Command Pilot Virgil Ivan "Gus" Grissom (B.S. 1950),
Senior Pilot Edward Higgins White II, and
Pilot Roger Bruce Chaffee (B.S. 1957). 
Gus Grissom before his mission said, "If we die, we want people to accept it. We are in a risky business, and we hope that if anything happens to us, it will not delay the program. The conquest of space is worth the risk of life." 
Ad astra per aspera. - To the stars through difficulties

Happy Memorial Day! Did you know the Purdue Memorial Union was named to recognize the 4,013 Boilermakers that enlisted in World War I? The black and gold tiled cross in the center of the Great Hall (pictured here) was laid to honor and remember the 67 Purdue students that gave their lives to the war. Since then, countless Boilermakers have gone on to fight for our country, and their memory is made permanent within the walls of the Great Hall. Spend some time taking a look around if you never have, there's a lot of history to be found!

Don't panic! Purdue is testing its emergency notification system, including sirens, at 10 am today (Sept. 30). The test will be used to ensure that the system's various layers are working properly.

Five Purdue professors have designed and are teaching a unique course this fall that provides a multidisciplinary perspective to global hunger. Called World Food Problems, the course consists of five sections with a total of 50 students. The goal, the faculty members say, is to combine Purdue's vast expertise in agricultural economics, consumer science, nutrition science and political science into a single course that teaches students a comprehensive view of global hunger.  

Pictured, students in the World Food Problems course talk with Dennis Savaiano, the Virginia C. Meredith Professor of Nutrition Policy, during one of the course's small-group discussions. (Purdue University/Charles Jischke) 

Read more about the course at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/purduetoday/releases/2014/Q3/world-food-problems-course-inspires-students-to-view-hunger-from-multiple-facets.html

Purdue's first president was Richard Owen, a Civil War veteran who was integral to the university's creation despite the fact that he served for less than two years. This year's freshmen class was welcomed to Purdue during a new student induction ceremony on Sunday. Here are some fun facts mentioned there about the first-year Boilermakers!

- More than 39,700 applications were received this year for approximately 6,400 first-year spaces
- The incoming class represents 1,879 different high schools
- In the Class of 2018, there are students from every corner of Indiana, 47 of 50 states and 48 countries
- The average high school GPA for this year's class is 3.72, which is an increase from last year
- 34.3% of the class achieved a perfect 4.0 GPA in high school
- 25.7% of this class had an ACT composite score of 30 or above and an SAT total of 2000 or above (while only 5% of students nation-wide achieved that high level)

We are so proud to honor Purdue sophomore Greg Cohen and employee Kevin Thedans for taking actions that likely saved a number of lives during an off-campus fire in the early morning of April 24 at Riverbend Apartments. 

Cohen, who was on his way to ROTC training, saw the smoke before any first responders had arrived. He quickly began waking those in the burning building so they could evacuate. Thedans arrived on the scene shortly afterward and helped. Their quick thinking, actions and courage ensured that the tragedy was not made worse.

On Thursday, President Daniels presented the One Brick Higher Award to them, which is given to people who go above and beyond the call of duty. 

Cody Day, 22, was killed in the fire. He was a Connersville resident who was not enrolled at Purdue and was visiting friends. Student Chase Woodall was injured in the fire and remains hospitalized at an Eskenazi Health facility in Indianapolis.

(Photo by Vincent Walters)

Known by many names since opening in 1909, Felix Haas Hall has a long and storied history. Originally known as Memorial Gymnasium, the building was built as a memorial to the football players, students and alumni who died in the famous 1903 Purdue train wreck.

The building hosted men's basketball games until 1938, when Lambert Fieldhouse was completed. Until that time, commencement ceremonies were held in the gym, which could easily be converted into an auditorium.

Read more about Haas Hall at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/purduetoday/didyouknow/2014/Q1/did-you-know-felix-haas-hall.html

TEDxPurdueU, Purdue's independently organized TED conference, is scheduled to host its annual flagship event from 1-6 p.m. March 7 in Loeb Playhouse.

The theme of TEDxPurdueU 2014 is "Daring Greatly," taken from the Theodore Roosevelt quote "The Man in the Arena." It urges the listener to strive towards one's goals - undeterred by failures, obstacles, or the status quo. Speakers who have lived these words will elaborate on how they have personally or professionally dared greatly to produce positive change in their own lives and communities.

For details, visit http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2014/Q1/tedxpurdueu-shares-speakers-who-have-dared-greatly.html

Purdue basketball coach Matt Painter has made it to the 3rd round of the 2014 Coaches' Charity Challenge, but is going to need help to advance forward! He is representing the Smith Family BReaK Thru Fund, a West Lafayette-based organization working to fight Niemann-Pick Type C Disease (NPC). The final round will run March 3-16 and the winning coach's charity will receive $100,000. The BReaK Thru Fund was set up in honor of a local family with three children impacted by NPC. Since its inception in 2008, the charity has funded more than $200,000 in research at Purdue.

The following statement from Purdue University President Mitch Daniels was delivered during a candlelight vigil on Tuesday (Jan. 21) evening for Andrew F. Boldt, 21, who was the victim of a campus shooting.

"Violent crime, whenever and wherever it occurs, shocks our conscience and incites our rage. When it happens in our home, to a family member ‚Äî and as a Boilermaker Andrew Boldt was family to us ‚Äî those emotions are more powerful still.

"Our prayers tonight are with Andrew and with his parents, who have suffered a loss beyond calculation or consolation. In our grief, we pause to thank this event's organizers, but equally each person in attendance. Through your caring witness, you are demonstrating your love for the Boldts, and for each other in the very special community we call 'Boilermakers.'"

A news conference has been scheduled for 6 p.m. ET today (Jan. 21) following the fatal shooting on the Purdue campus. It will be webcast at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2014/Q1/january-21%2C-2014%2C-6-p.m.-news-conference.html

UPDATE: Out of respect for the Boilermaker community and in light of today's tragic fatal shooting on campus, Purdue will cancel any remaining classes today and all classes tomorrow.

Counselors will be available to talk with students, faculty and staff. For information on counseling services, visit http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2014/Q1/classes-suspended,-counseling-offered-in-wake-of-shooting.html

Purdue officials announced that due to current and predicted adverse weather conditions, normal operations have been suspended on the West Lafayette campus.

Staff members predesignated as "essential personnel" should follow their departmental procedures, and nonessential personnel should not report to campus, beginning at 6 tonight (Jan. 5) and continuing for all shifts on Monday (Jan. 6).

The suspension does not affect students, who are not scheduled to begin classes until Monday (Jan. 13). University Residences plans to open remaining halls for returning students as planned at 8 a.m. Tuesday (Jan. 7).

Sunday's severe storms caused power outages across the Purdue University campus. Thankfully, a majority of campus buildings and residence halls have since had power restored. A handful of campus facilities not serviced by the university power plant continue be without power. Utility crews are working to restore power to those buildings as soon as possible.
 
Students who remain without power can access facilities at the France A. Cordova Recreational Sports Center at 355 N. Martin Jischke Drive if needed.  Students are asked to bring their own towels and toiletries. The Co-Rec's hours are 5:30 a.m. - midnight.
 
Residential Life has made an arrangement with Ford Dining Court for students without power (and without a meal plan) at Hilltop Apartments. Affected students should bring their Purdue ID with them to swipe for meals. Hilltop Building 23 in the main office can be used to charge phones.
 
Students needing further help should contact the Student Assistance Center in the Office of the Dean of Students at (765) 494-1747 or by email at odosmain@purdue.edu.

Purdue University is still experiencing power outages, primarily with the sections of campus that are on the Duke Energy power grid.

The central part of campus does have power, as it it supplied by Purdue's power plant. If you venture on to campus please use caution, as several traffic signals are still out.

Purdue.edu is currently offline, along with several online services, but ITaP is working to have them up and running soon.

The 2013 Nobel Prize in physics today, Oct. 8, was awarded to Fran√ßois Englert and Peter Higgs for their work in developing the theory of the Higgs field, and Purdue University researchers were part of the international experiment that proved its existence.

Purdue's particle physics group has been among the team of international scientists working on experiments at the European Organization for Nuclear Research, or CERN, laboratory and the hunt for the Higgs boson for more than two decades. In July of 2012, their work culminated in an historical moment when representatives of the international collaboration announced the discovery of the Higgs particle, which proves the existence of the Higgs field. Photo, of the CMS, or Compact Muon Solenoid detector at CERN is by Maximlien Brice. 

More: http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2013/Q4/theory-of-higgs-field-earns-nobel-prize,-purdue-physicists-part-of-experiment-that-proved-it.html

The next phase of Purdue Cardinal Community Hoops is about to begin as the first court restoration nears completion. The program, started in 2012 by Purdue Trademarks and Licensing, was designed to create partnerships to take on projects such as restoring the basketball court in Lafayette's Murdock Park, which had  been in need of major repairs. Brian Cardinal, former Purdue basketball great and current member of the Boilermaker athletic staff, will be joined by several dignitaries on Thursday, Sept. 26, for the dedication of the newly restored court. The project started last spring and includes new backboards, lights, some seating, court resurfacing, painting the court to look like Mackey Arena's floor and bearing the name Purdue Cardinal Community Hoops.

Did you know that the origin of Purdue's official colors goes back to 1887 ‚Äî just 13 years after the university began offering classes? The decision to adopt old gold and black is attributed to the captain of Purdue's first football team, John Breckenridge Burris. Also, according to at least one source, the designation was rather hasty, says David Hovde, associate professor of library science. 

Read more about the choice at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/purduetoday/didyouknow/2013/Q3/did-you-know-old-gold-and-black.html

A mystery of the moon that imperiled astronauts and spacecraft on lunar missions has been solved by a Purdue University-led team of scientists as part of NASA's GRAIL mission. Jay Melosh, a Purdue distinguished professor of earth, atmospheric and planetary sciences, stands in front of a map showing the moon's gravity field. As a member of the science team of NASA's Gravity Recovery and Interior Laboratory mission, Melosh led a study of large concentrations of mass beneath the lunar surface. The team confirmed that the mass concentrations, or "mascons," were caused by massive asteroid impacts billions of year ago and determined how these impacts changed the density of material on the moon's surface and, in turn, its gravity field. 

Read more about the research at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2013/Q2/purdue-led-team-solves-one-of-the-moons-mysteries.html

(Purdue University photo/Mark Simons; image of lunar gravity field courtesy of NASA)

A team of Purdue students has designed a new type of prosthetic leg for 5-year-old Lucas Resch, who has a rare birth defect that makes his left leg far shorter than his right. At left are conventional prosthetics, which do not give Lucas the ability to run and ride a bicycle or play like his friends. The new prosthetic leg, not shown, uses an innovative gearbox design that enables the prosthetic to move more like a real leg. (Photo provided by Resch family)

Many homeowners with drought-damaged lawns have some decisions to make about how to repair them now that it's the season. Aaron Patton, a Purdue turf grass Extension specialist, says it mostly comes down to answering this question: Do I reseed, or will fertilizing be enough to recover my lawn? He says if the damaged area is larger than the size of a hand print, then it most likely needs to be reseeded. (Purdue Agricultural Communication photo/Keith Robinson) 

http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2012/Q3/purdue-extension-has-advice-for-repairing-drought-damaged-lawns.html

In the basement of Purdue's EE Building exists a curious sight: A 17-foot-deep, well-like structure filled with water and surrounded by equipment that seems straight out of science fiction. The facility, however, is anything but make-believe. It's the Purdue University Reactor No. 1, or PUR-1, and it's been helping nuclear engineering students understand the intricacies of nuclear fission since 1962. Jere Jenkins, pictured here, is the facility director. Read more at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/purduetoday/didyouknow/2012/did-you-know-purdue-reactor-no.-1.html  (Purdue University/Mark Simons)

status_message:
I am an American.
That's the way most of us put it, just matter of factly. 
They are plain words, those four. 
You could write them on your thumbnail, 
or you could sweep them clear across this bright autumn sky.
But remember too that they are more than words.
They are a way of life.
So whenever you speak them, speak them firmly;
speak them proudly; speak them gratefully. 
I am an American.

In a small workshop deep within Stewart Center, workers have been toiling since May to build wooden props that look more than a little out of season. Snow-covered evergreen trees and large mounds of the wintry substance are taking shape there, all in preparation for the 79th annual Purdue Christmas Show, scheduled for Dec. 1 and 2. Summer might seem early for building Christmas Show set pieces, but the production's organizers say that getting a head start is a key to the show's success. Hall of Music Productions theater technicians Dallas Johnson (left) and J.D. Fackler work on a wooden set piece for this year's show. (Purdue University photo/Mark Simons)

Ten miles from Purdue's campus, there exists a verdant biological sciences laboratory containing more than 100 animal species and more than 400 varieties of plants. It's located in the Ross Biological Reserve ‚Äî 92 acres of mature forest, stretched along the Wabash River and complete with towering tree canopies, rolling vistas and burbling creeks. It is home to Purdue classes, research and outreach projects. http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/purduetoday/general/2012/120716_RossReserve.html (Purdue University photo/Mark Simons)

New Purdue research shows that frequent child abuse by a parent can increase a child's cancer risk in adulthood, and the effects are especially significant when mothers abuse their daughters and fathers abuse their sons. The research was conducted by Kenneth Ferraro, distinguished professor of sociology and director of Purdue's Center on Aging and the Life Course, and sociology and gerontology graduate student Patricia Morton. Read more about the research at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/research/2012/120717FerraroChildren.html (Purdue University photo/Mark Simons)

Ever wonder why your smartphone's battery is draining so fast? It might be the free apps. Purdue researchers have shown that popular free smartphone apps spend up to 75 percent of their energy tracking the user's geographical location, sending information about the user to advertisers and downloading ads.

"It turns out the free apps aren't really free because they contain the hidden cost of reduced battery life," said Y. Charlie Hu, a Purdue University professor of electrical and computer engineering. 

http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/research/2012/120404HuSmartphone.htm
link_name: Purdue Newsroom - Free apps drain smartphone energy on 'advertising modules'

Leading Purdue entomologist Ralph Williams, an international expert in the use of insects to help solve crimes, will deliver the next Science on Tap talk tonight (March 29) in downtown Lafayette. Williams will speak at 6 p.m. in the upstairs of the Lafayette Brewing Company, 622 Main St., in Lafayette. His presentation, Forensic Entomology: Use of Insects in Crime Scene Investigations and Legal Situations, is free and open to the public to those ages 21 or older. http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/events/2012/120323WilliamsScienceOnTap.html

status_message: Research led by Michael G. Heinz, an associate professor of speech, language and hearing sciences who specializes in auditory neuroscience, shows how the inner ear processes the temporal structure of sound. These findings could someday improve how prosthetic hearing devices are designed to help people with profound hearing loss hear better in noisy places. The findings were published last month in The Journal of Neuroscience. Read more about the research at http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/research/2012/120327HeinzHearing.html (Purdue University photo/Andrew Hancock)

status_message: Congratulations to Don Thompson, Purdue graduate and member of the Board of Trustees, who has been named as the next chief executive officer of McDonald's Corp. Thompson is currently president and chief operating officer at McDonald's. His new role will begin July 1, when the current CEO Jim Skinner retires. Thompson received his B.S. in electrical engineering in 1984 from Purdue and has since accepted the Purdue University Outstanding Electrical and Computer Engineering Award along with being named a Purdue University Old Master Fellow in 2006.

A group of Purdue engineering and technology students will soon begin work on a 2013 Chevrolet Malibu as part of an international competition designed to reduce the environmental impact of passenger vehicles. The effort is part of EcoCAR2, a program established by the U.S. Department of Energy and General Motors. Only 15 universities are competing in the competition. http://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/research/2012/120319MotevalliEcoCar.html
